---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro'
import Header from '../components/Header.astro'
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro'
---

<Base title="Terms of Service — Extol">
  <Header />

  <main class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">
    <h1 class="font-serif text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-600 text-bark-900 mb-2">Terms of Service</h1>
    <p class="text-sm text-warm-gray-400 mb-1"><strong>Effective Date:</strong> March 13, 2026</p>
    <p class="text-sm text-warm-gray-400 mb-12"><strong>Last Updated:</strong> March 16, 2026</p>

    <div class="prose">
      <h2 id="agreement-to-terms">1. Agreement to Terms</h2>
      <p>
        By accessing or using the Extol platform, including the Brij community
        event tool and any associated services (collectively, the "Services"),
        you agree to be bound by these Terms of Service ("Terms"). If you do not
        agree to these Terms, do not use the Services.
      </p>
      <p>
        "We," "us," and "Extol" refer to Extol, Inc. "You" and "your" refer to
        the individual or entity accessing the Services.
      </p>

      <h2 id="description-of-services">2. Description of Services</h2>

      <h3>2.1 Brij</h3>
      <p>Brij is a community event coordination tool that enables:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Creation and management of community events</li>
        <li>Attendance tracking and check-in</li>
        <li>Recording of contributions and activities</li>
        <li>Peer attestations within communities</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Brij is available as open-source software under the Apache License 2.0.
        The hosted version of Brij on the Extol platform is subject to these
        Terms.
      </p>

      <h3>2.2 Extol Platform</h3>
      <p>
        The Extol platform provides governance infrastructure for voluntary
        communities, including:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Community formation and governance tools</li>
        <li>Collective organization under the Contributor Commons Agreement (CCA)</li>
        <li>On-chain attestations on the Solana blockchain</li>
        <li>Community governance tokens</li>
        <li>Cross-community identity and reputation services</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>2.3 Free and Paid Tiers</h3>
      <p>
        Certain features of the Services are available at no charge. Premium
        features are available through paid subscription plans as described on
        our pricing page. We reserve the right to modify pricing with 30 days'
        advance notice.
      </p>

      <h2 id="account-registration">3. Account Registration</h2>

      <h3>3.1 Account Creation</h3>
      <p>
        To use certain features of the Services, you must create an account.
        You agree to:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Provide accurate and complete registration information</li>
        <li>Maintain the security of your account credentials</li>
        <li>Promptly update your information if it changes</li>
        <li>Accept responsibility for all activity under your account</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>3.2 Age Requirements</h3>
      <p>
        You must be at least 13 years old to create an account or use the
        Services. In jurisdictions where the digital age of consent is higher
        than 13 (including certain EU/EEA member states where it may be up to
        16), the local age of digital consent applies. If you are under 18, you
        represent that your parent or legal guardian has reviewed and agreed to
        these Terms on your behalf.
      </p>
      <p>
        For communities that serve participants under 13 (or under the local
        age of digital consent), additional parental consent requirements apply.
        See our COPPA Compliance section (Section 11).
      </p>

      <h3>3.3 Coordinator Accounts</h3>
      <p>
        Community coordinators who record attendance or activities on behalf of
        other participants represent that:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>The participant actually participated in the recorded event</li>
        <li>They have a good-faith basis for creating records on the
          participant's behalf</li>
        <li>They understand the participant will be notified and may review or
          delete the record</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="user-content-and-contributions">4. User Content and Contributions</h2>

      <h3>4.1 Your Content</h3>
      <p>
        You retain ownership of all content you submit to the Services,
        including event descriptions, activity records, contributions, and peer
        attestations ("User Content").
      </p>
      <p>
        By submitting User Content, you grant Extol a non-exclusive, worldwide,
        royalty-free license to use, store, display, and process your User
        Content solely to provide and improve the Services. This license
        terminates when you delete your content or account, subject to
        Section 4.3.
      </p>

      <h3>4.2 Contributor Commons Agreement</h3>
      <p>
        If you participate in a Collective under the Contributor Commons
        Agreement (CCA), your Contributions are governed by the CCA in addition
        to these Terms. In the event of a conflict between these Terms and the
        CCA with respect to Contributions, the CCA controls.
      </p>

      <h3>4.3 On-Chain Data</h3>
      <p>
        If your community activates Extol governance features, certain data may
        be recorded as on-chain attestations on the Solana blockchain. Activation
        of on-chain features requires your consent. You may opt out of on-chain
        features while retaining access to Brij coordination tools (see Privacy
        Policy Section 7.5). You acknowledge that:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>On-chain data is public and permanent — it cannot be deleted from the
          blockchain</li>
        <li>Attestations use pseudonymous wallet addresses, not your name or
          personal information</li>
        <li>Extol maintains the connection between your identity and your wallet
          address; this connection can be severed upon account deletion (see
          Section 9)</li>
        <li>On-chain attestations may include hashed records of participation,
          governance token balances, and staking positions</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>4.4 Prohibited Content</h3>
      <p>You may not submit content that:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Is unlawful, fraudulent, or deceptive</li>
        <li>Infringes any third party's intellectual property or privacy rights</li>
        <li>Contains malware or disruptive code</li>
        <li>Impersonates another person or entity</li>
        <li>Is designed to manipulate governance mechanisms or attestation scores</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="community-governance">5. Community Governance</h2>

      <h3>5.1 Community Rules</h3>
      <p>
        Individual communities may adopt governance rules (Bylaws) consistent
        with the CCA and these Terms. Community Bylaws may impose additional
        requirements on members beyond these Terms, including:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Contribution standards and quality requirements</li>
        <li>Governance participation expectations</li>
        <li>Membership tiers and eligibility criteria</li>
        <li>Revenue distribution formulas</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>5.2 Standing and Credit</h3>
      <p>
        Communities that activate Extol governance earn two types of community
        tokens, determined by each member's chosen allocation:
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Standing</strong> (governance commitment):
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Permanently locked to your community — cannot be transferred, traded,
          or withdrawn</li>
        <li>Determines your governance weight (square-root weighted voting power)</li>
        <li>Represents your commitment to this community</li>
        <li>Irrevocable — the more you lock, the more voice you have</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <strong>Credit</strong> (portable balance):
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Portable within the Extol network</li>
        <li>Usable within the internal community economy</li>
        <li>Cannot be exchanged for dollars, sold on public markets, or purchased
          with money</li>
        <li>Earned only through participation — not purchasable</li>
        <li>Reflects recent activity (balances depreciate over time if not used)</li>
        <li>Designed for governance participation and community utility, not as
          investments</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Credit operates as a closed-loop internal system, similar to loyalty
        points or rewards programs. Credit has no public market value and is
        not convertible to currency.
      </p>

      <h3>5.3 Public Exchangeability (Community Opt-In)</h3>
      <p>
        Individual communities may vote through their governance process to
        enable public exchangeability for their tokens. This is an upgrade
        from the default closed-loop model and requires:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>The community has achieved sufficient governance maturity, including
          formation as a Decentralized Unincorporated Nonprofit Association
          (DUNA) or equivalent governance structure demonstrating independent,
          member-driven decision-making</li>
        <li>A governance vote by the community's members</li>
        <li>Fresh consent from each member (see Section 4.3)</li>
        <li>Compliance with additional regulatory requirements</li>
        <li>Migration to self-custody wallets</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Public exchangeability is not the default. Most communities operate
        entirely within the internal credit system. Extol does not encourage
        or promote public exchangeability — it is available as an option for
        communities whose needs require it.
      </p>

      <h3>5.4 Platform Governance</h3>
      <p>
        Changes to the Extol platform that affect all communities — including
        changes to these Terms, the CCA, and platform-wide policies — are
        subject to a governance process that includes Collective input, as
        described in the Platform Governance Charter.
      </p>

